We distributed numerous prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how even larger prizes might have impacted participation, such as offering a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This might have helped counteract the drop in engagement the project faced. The nature of the prizes remained consistent throughout the project. However, increasing the value of the prizes over time might have been beneficial. While the gift cards were sufficient at the project's start, announcing additional incentives like bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January could have potentially boosted participation and engagement, rather than seeing a decline.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all fifteen trick films made between 1895 and 1901. These films typically utilize creative editing to create illusions. My analysis primarily focused on describing the artistic elements of most trick films and identifying unique evolutionary traits in a few of the later ones. Generally, trick films from the turn of the century were confined to a set, shot within a frontal proscenium, lacked camera movement, employed long and medium shots, and followed a strict one shot equals one film approach. However, some films from the early 1900s began to challenge these norms by incorporating multiple shots.

A prominent feature shared by these trick films is the use of an interior set framed by a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary, not tracking any movement of figures or objects. This style was typical of early films, influenced by theatrical traditions and, specifically for trick films, vaudeville and magic performances. One limitation of this stage-based approach is that characters in trick films mainly move side-to-side, without approaching or retreating from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move horizontally. Even when they exit the frame, the camera stays in place.

The frontal proscenium composition also results in mostly long shots, with medium shots being less common, and no close-ups appearing in any of the Edison trick films. This mirrors the theatre and vaudeville conventions, where audiences saw the entire performance framed by the stage boundaries. As with most early films, actors do not move towards the camera from the middle ground, so close-ups are absent.

Typically, early trick films follow the principle that a single conceptual shot constitutes a whole film. This restricts the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frame rate used, and limits their dramatic or narrative potential; they mainly focus on short vaudeville-like tricks, such as magic or disappearing acts, with minimal story. However, in trick films, a conceptual shot perceived by the viewer doesn’t necessarily mean a single physical shot. A “shot” might actually comprise several edited together to create illusions of appearance or disappearance. For example, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a closer examination reveals the transition to the shot with Mary's severed "head," even though the entire film is perceived as one continuous shot by the viewer.

The classic "Gothic Novel" is, as Ian Watt points out in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, an oxymoron signifying "Old-New." This literary style has been both criticized and praised, accused of lacking depth, and admired for its ability to evoke a 'terrible sublime' (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the first "Gothic Novel," combined elements from both "ancient and modern" romances to forge the proto-Gothic genre and a new way of literary expression. Walpole incorporated "old" theatrical traditions with 'new' natural mimicry from 'modern' novels to create what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre extensively references medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and customs. Even during the publication of The Castle of Otranto, "gothic" described various peoples, styles, and eras, often seen as outdated or crude compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The blend of theatrical "Gothic" with the novel's new format, which offered readers a more intimate glimpse into characters' psychology, has enabled the Gothic to endure over time, being simultaneously obsolete and fresh to readers far removed from its inception.

A key gothic theme in Gothic novels is the idea of Chivalry. In The Castle of Otranto, the medieval concept of chivalry—the training of a proper knight—is both preserved and transformed. Chivalry holds significant appeal for Gothic authors because it symbolizes the classic knight, brave, honorable, and capable, and the perceived absence of such ideals in society, as seen by writers like Walpole. By employing chivalric ideals and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing the Gothic's evolution into Romantic) and is used to critique and potentially enhance the present. When writing The Castle of Otranto, Walpole was amidst political turmoil and despondent about the future. Immersed in politics and possibly facing unjust accusations, he might have, even if subconsciously, felt that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" of the gothic era had been lost in contemporary society. This sentiment is evident in his characters, such as Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, readers learn he embodies many chivalric traits; he is depicted as:

Frederic's description is filled with traditional chivalric imagery; he is primarily a prince, who has endured suffering, been properly affected by tragedy, left his home, and is believed to have been slain by infidels. The portrayal of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses the sequence of actions required to transfer goods from a customer's order through the stages of raw materials, supply, production, and distribution until they reach the customer. The concept of supply chain management was introduced in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. He explained the comprehensive process of planning, executing, and overseeing supply chain activities to meet customer needs promptly and efficiently. The six essential components of a supply chain are production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers utilize these elements to deliver optimal customer service.

The initial step in the supply chain process is production, which serves as the basis for the entire system. This stage involves determining the timing, reasoning, location, and methodology for production. Managers must understand customer preferences, which can be gauged by examining the market. The market is a primary indicator of customer demands. Once managers have assessed the market and comprehend customer needs, they can decide on the products to be manufactured and their quantities. After these decisions, they choose the most suitable production site, considering factors like volume and quality while ensuring customer demands and satisfaction are met. Following the selection of a production location, managers concentrate on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is a critical phase in the supply chain, where attention to detail is crucial, as inadequate planning can result in significant time and financial losses for the company. For instance, in my experience at Wal-Mart and Target, both companies had structured guidelines and processes for various business aspects, including employee uniforms and shipment receipt. Clearly defined processes enable smooth operation without confusion about direction and expectations.

The second crucial component of supply chain management is supply. Supply involves making strategic decisions to determine a facility’s core capabilities, which subsequently guide the development of outsourcing partnerships. A company might have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with distinct equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers need to identify which division is best suited for different stages of production. They might also opt to outsource work to other companies, primarily to achieve velocity. Velocity refers to the capacity to deliver quality and flexibility while simultaneously reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the era. However, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights are considered Victorian novels that deviate from this norm. These two works incorporate elements of mystery and a penchant for the unusual, which are not typical of the period's literature, thereby enhancing the characters and providing deeper insights into their motives and emotions.

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of firearms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

Both novels frequently use mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and purpose differ in each case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner struggles, his pain, and his awareness of the true nature of the events around him. When Oliver's shooting is revisited in chapter 28, he experiences the event as if in a vivid dream, struggling to find help. The passage highlights Oliver’s lack of control over unfolding events and the severe state of his health, as emphasized by his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing his senses so much that he fails to notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he relives his despair, now intertwined with constant pain and fear rather than surprise. This raises the question of who is responsible for his misfortune, as it was clearly not his own doing. The shooting underscores Oliver's lack of control, showing that he cannot even attempt to alter the outcome of events, even when his life is at stake. This passage suggests a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, compelling him to accept this despair and affecting his ability to respond. Otherwise, it could be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least to save his own life.

"The day passed off—day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come—and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years back, I was involved in an after-school program where I tutored elementary students. I tried my best to assist them in any subject they found challenging, although my expertise was in English and reading. An instructor asked me to help a young boy named Adrian, likely in third or fourth grade, who was facing significant difficulties with reading. I noticed something unusual; he had inconsistent issues with letter pronunciation—some he nailed perfectly, while others were completely off. Adrian was clearly of Latino descent, yet he spoke flawless English. We struggled until one day I met his mother. I was looking after a few students left behind while the rest went on a field trip when she came in. She didn't speak English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish skills, we managed to understand each other. It then struck me: Adrian was proficient in reading but wasn't well-versed in the English alphabet. I can't say for sure if this realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. It also illustrates that these challenges aren't always apparent. Even a child fluent in spoken English can face significant hurdles in reading. We all recognize this problem, but what's the solution? In Adrian's situation, the fix was straightforward: focused tutoring in English reading, especially on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for children with limited English skills, the solution is more complex. There's no single answer. A combination of dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, and ESL classes is essential.

To begin, the dual language system is a promising approach, beneficial not just for Spanish-speaking children but for all. Research shows that children in bilingual programs often outperform their peers academically. Despite concerns that such programs might squander resources or benefit only a few, this is untrue. If these programs became standard rather than exceptions, all students would gain. But how do we implement this? Demanding all teachers to be bilingual isn't practical. Nevertheless, there's no reason we can't employ bilingual aides or tutors.

From a young age, many of us are taught that there exists something greater than ourselves, something beyond our comprehension. Some of us attend Sunday school to learn about it, others go to Temple, or seek answers within. Many easily accept the religions passed down by our parents, while others reject them entirely, believing nothing exists beyond their personal, self-centered world. We might embrace one set of beliefs only to later adopt another. Regardless of the path we take, we strive to understand ourselves through our own spiritual perspectives, seeking a guiding light to lead us from darkness to light.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on our front porch, listening to the rain on the tin roof while we smoked. The gutters overflowed, soaking the plants by the porch. My father stared into the rain, a gaze that seemed both searching and remembering. He had become thinner, his clothes hanging loosely, and his hair was sparser than I remembered. He continued to look into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt isolated, frightened, unable to express how much I would miss him, fearing that speaking about it would make it more real. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the June twilight rain.

My father passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation only prolonged his suffering beyond the doctors’ expectations, providing no comfort. I questioned the kind of God who would allow this. Alone at night, I offered no prayers, thinking if God existed, He had stopped listening to me long ago.

I didn’t want to witness his transition from this life to another, so I didn’t. I couldn’t watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father wouldn’t want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and fervent supporter of Republicanism. Though he was mainly a farmer, his profession and brief political career made him known for his commitment and outspoken views on personal freedom and governance. His belief in an agrarian system formed the foundation of nearly all his governmental opinions. His efforts to uphold and promote what he saw as the noblest profession shaped his views on sovereignty, constitutionality, and the judicial system.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique chance to establish an ideal system, as there was no existing tradition to constrain the government’s founders, enabling the creation of a self-governing system. He was a strong advocate for natural rights and believed they were interlinked—if one right is denied, all will fail, diminishing the value of the remaining rights. Therefore, these rights should be protected from government interference. He argued that in the so-called "state of nature," those with physical strength and cunning intelligence thrived, but this should not be the case in a civilized society.

To create this ideal society, Taylor argued for a government that acknowledges the inherent good and evil within humans. He held firm views on dualistic morality, stating, “As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human” (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that safeguard private property, enhance agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing a government based on such principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by greed and self-interest. Taylor saw self-interest as a universal motivator but considered it only evil when it led to the formation of sub-societies that thrived at others’ expense. A good government was essential to restrain man's inherent evil, requiring constant vigilance to prevent the incorporation of harmful principles.

Like many committed Republicans of his era, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He favored a highly limited Federal government, permitting only the rights and powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He recognized that a large Federal government was costly and likely to become tyrannical. However, he believed that a straightforward, literal interpretation could be perilous, as it could easily become corrupt without considering the writers’ intentions. Furthermore, he viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true foundation of the United States, as it more clearly defined the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I gazed downward, my mind trying to take in the view without attaching any deeper meaning to it. With a calm detachment and a practiced eye, I examined the scene before me, my thoughts fleeting in and out so quickly that it felt as if I wasn't really thinking, just experiencing the sight fluidly. 

Once, following a suggestion from an artist I knew, I bought a book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had longed to learn drawing since I was six, and this book covered everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One method it taught was to use a square frame to focus on any picture, simplifying a complex scene—like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room—into a more manageable image, just the fruit on a simple surface.

At that moment, staring at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally apply the artist’s frame. I was too overwhelmed, too struck with awe, only able to stand and marvel. Picasso had his blue period, Monet adored greenery, and the Italian Renaissance masters reveled in a spectrum of colors. If I fancied my viewpoint to be worthy of the title "Artistic," then the scene before me was the inception of my piece, my story, Work in Brown.

My fingers touched my chosen tool of creativity, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved, my mind's intent taking shape in what might have been my most creative moment. Water swirled, calm and clear, as particles broke away and disappeared. Muscles tightened, jerking more anxiously the second time as my hand hit the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown mass remained, stuck like a slug at the toilet’s bottom.

Holding the mop loosely, feet apart, and my green tie uncomfortably tight, I frowned at the unpleasant bundle of processed matter left as a message for the unlucky ones cleaning the Rite Aid bathrooms. Several more flushes, a few more calm moments of introspection, then my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teen fatalities in car accidents are a growing concern. Various factors contribute to this alarming trend among the youngest drivers in America. According to the National Institutes of Health, one issue is that teenagers' brains are not fully developed to handle the dangers of driving. Additionally, their lack of experience greatly contributes to the problem, leading to more fatal crashes, increased instances of rollovers, speeding, and veering off the road. Teenagers are particularly at risk when driving with peers, a common occurrence. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a link between the age of passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents. 

To address this, California and other states have introduced provisional licenses that limit driving hours and restrict other minors from being passengers. However, these measures are temporary solutions. The fundamental problem is that young drivers, as a group, are statistically unable to manage driving risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman suggests that even at 18, individuals may be too young for a standard driver's license. His research, cited by USA Today, indicates that people under 19-20 often seek risky experiences for excitement. It would be logical to postpone driving until this thrill-seeking tendency diminishes. Issuing licenses to young teens could lead to even more deadly accidents, potentially increasing fatalities as more Baby Boomer offspring become eligible to drive by 2010.

Legislation to address this could be relatively simple. Schools could continue offering driver's education to prepare future drivers, but no one under 18 should drive. A provisional permit could still be issued before a full license, requiring a set number of driving hours, similar to existing state requirements (such as California's six hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours with an adult). Since teen driving fatalities are a nationwide issue, uniform national legislation would be an effective way to safeguard teenagers across the country. This proposal is not a new concept.

This document explores three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with a concise definition of the disorder, followed by an explanation of the diagnosis process, highlighting common characteristics or "red flags." The paper concludes by discussing how teachers in mainstream classrooms can support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), pertains to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. More specifically, (C)AP involves the CNS's perceptual processing of auditory information and the neurobiological activity that supports this processing, which results in electrophysiologic auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Essentially, it is a disorder where the brain struggles to process auditory inputs correctly. Individuals with CAPD can hear normally and are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain area responsible for interpreting auditory information, such as distinguishing words or separating conversation from background noise, does not function as expected.

The earliest reference to what is now known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s under the term "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), during research on children with communication disorders. The Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and developed a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system (CANS) related to dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 sparked further research into CAPD in children.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: individuals may struggle to locate or perceive sound spatially, have difficulty distinguishing between multiple sounds, fail to recognize sound patterns, or be unable to detect changes in speech tone (such as sarcasm). Sounds may be masked by subsequent sounds, there may be an inability to synthesize auditory clues meaningfully, and there might be difficulty identifying the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

Diagnosing CAPD involves screening through "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which can be conducted by audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and other professionals using various measures to assess auditory-related skills (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires, surveys, and observations of auditory behaviors, such as the patient's responses to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test with consistently high diagnostic success, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many tests present the patient with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and require them to differentiate certain items, such as words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the corresponding responses.

In my pursuit of a social work education, my goal is to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services, focusing on assisting children who have experienced abuse or neglect and offering support to families in distress. The values I bring to the field of social work include service, respect, ethical conduct, a commitment to enhancing relationships, and a dedication to my own professional development to ensure competence in my field. These principles are not only vital to social workers but also personally significant to me.

I have always wanted to help others, though I was initially uncertain about which career path to choose. During my high school and college years, I observed many people avoiding their issues or adopting inadequate coping strategies. These experiences motivated me to earn a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still unsure of my career direction, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. That summer, a visit to a friend introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy seeking refuge from abusive parents. The next day, when he contacted the police regarding his home situation, I visited his parents' house to see if I could assist. I shared my concerns with the police, mentioning my recent psychology degree, and they asked me to speak with the parents since legal action could not be taken for the teenager. In questioning the parents, they appeared anxious and offered excuses, describing their son's actions as manipulative in involving outsiders for what they called "simple" family disputes. This experience made me seriously consider a career in social work to assist children facing "simple" family conflicts.

Social justice is another crucial value in social work. While society professes the importance of the individual and mourns those we lose, it often values conformity over genuine individuality. If society truly values the individual, why do we strive to be like everyone else? I consider myself an individual and resist conforming to societal norms. Throughout high school and college, I opposed social injustice through various means, such as dyeing my hair unconventional colors, wearing clothes that reflected my personality, getting multiple ear piercings, participating in GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and standing against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I am committed to social justice and will continue to challenge social injustices.

This paper examines the Biological and Sociocultural models as they pertain to insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic traits and medical health factors. In contrast, the Sociocultural model considers environmental interactions and their relevance to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review analyzes research on insomnia, clarifying how each study relates to and enhances the understanding of these models, while also assessing the strengths and weaknesses of the findings.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary disorders, those linked to another mental disorder, or those associated with other conditions. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, whereas disorders related to mental health are connected to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders might arise from medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias comprise Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves challenges in achieving or maintaining sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake, both persisting for at least a month. Narcolepsy is characterized by cataplexy and/or automatic REM sleep. While Dyssomnias focus on sleep onset and maintenance, Parasomnias involve behavioral or physiological abnormalities during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Disorders linked to other mental health issues involve sleep disturbances caused by Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Intellectual Disabilities). This review centers on insomnia, with a partial focus on primary sleep disorders, in relation to biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetic, hereditary, and physiological aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus that contain orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. Research on mice demonstrated that GABAB receptors on orexin neurons are crucial for sleep/wake regulation. Activation of the GABAA receptor promotes sleep, and inhibiting it may reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist baclofen was shown to increase sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that results from animal studies may be applicable to humans, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. Issues with this receptor could impair sleep without medication. Socioculturally, if such a phenotype is inherited, it could disrupt sleep naturally, adversely affecting areas like education, employment, and daily tasks requiring concentration.

I have been attending University Park for approximately two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many students, myself included. During my freshman year, I was assigned a dorm room in East Halls, which is nearly at the easternmost edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my residence at Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially during the frequent inclement weather in State College. An alum, not much older than me, shared that in the past, East Halls were separated from the rest of the university by vast stretches of unused land. Nowadays, that space has been developed with sports fields, large new buildings such as the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to grow, moving around becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best way to tackle this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, simply having bikes isn't enough. Students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must cater to cyclists' needs.

I recently spoke to a friend who started cycling again after several years. He remarked that he wondered why he ever stopped, saying, “Bikes are great. For a while, it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” Besides being beneficial for health, cycling is the most efficient mode of transport. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many other undergraduates, I now live off-campus, at a distance comparable to some dorms from the campus center. The smartest choice I made this year was buying a bike. I have a class in the Thomas building daily, which is a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Biking can reduce that time to just 5 minutes if I ride fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, can be challenging to travel on, whether by bike or on foot. Walking has its advantages, but personally, I’m too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, totaling over two and a half hours each week. This doesn't include all the additional time I'd spend walking to other classes and appointments. That's more time than I can afford to lose.

In "Brave New World," Aldous Huxley critiques the looming dangers of technology and the capitalist framework that supports it by depicting a dystopian society. In this society, individuals prioritize community over personal identity and are conditioned from birth to seek immediate gratification above all else. The citizens are mere instruments in a larger scheme, restricted to a single ideology as directed by the World Controller. A Marxist analysis of the novel reveals Huxley's underlying concerns about the growth of these systems. Marxist concepts like homogeny and reification help underscore that Huxley's work critiques the flaws in the emerging economy of his era.

Capitalism is mocked using the Marxist concept of false consciousness, where ordinary people are kept from understanding their true economic relationships with other classes because they are focused on personal gain. This is attributed to the ideological control over the proletariat and common laborers, clearly demonstrated by the conditioning in "Brave New World." The lower classes, such as Delta and Gamma, lack true autonomy; hypnopaedia enforces their desire to consume and indulge above all else, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the domination of social classes by another group, is evident here. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that sustains capitalist and consumerist structures. The upper classes, born with awareness, largely do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, like Bernard, challenge their roles. The interactions between social classes highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In "Brave New World," authentic relationships between individuals do not exist. The novel intentionally avoids distinguishing its characters, even major ones, who lack depth. Huxley may be suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism strips individuals of free will and self-expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent, with interactions remaining superficial, as shown by male characters' comments on women's physical traits and women's candid discussions about their encounters. Additionally, each class's acceptance of its position in the hierarchy reflects the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their complete compliance with their societal role illustrates Marxist views on the proletariat, falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform with their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC. A major topic of intense debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I feel that this question is even more pertinent today than it was before. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I have seen the mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I doubt that back in 2001, we would have ever seen a presidential candidate with the name Barack Obama, who has a clear Muslim heritage in his family.

The Prophet's biography fascinates me because, based on what I know of Muhammad's history, it seems to contradict his personality. From my past knowledge and learning, I believed that Muhammad compelled conversions to Islam. He would conquer tribes and then force them to adopt Islam. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and humble before others, after which people gradually came to acknowledge the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Additionally, there are striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. Most notably, he multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men. This style of writing suggests that the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet who needed no validation, living simply in truth and miracles. This kind of portrayal is problematic because it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems like they are trying to take credit for Jesus's life and identity through Muhammad.

Moreover, the biography contains numerous stories suggesting that part of its aim is to provide evidence of how people supposedly 'independently' converted to Islam. However, many stories are from at least a third-party perspective, with the author describing information as heard from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I found this troubling because, even though their intention was to provide proof of the stories' truth, it seemed to undermine the stories and make them more suspicious.

What troubles me most about this work is how they attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly figure who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. Yet, history contradicts the notion of Muhammad as a gentle and humble man, and I wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus were quickly set aside as Christian thought developed after his life. Looking at history broadly, Christianity appears to have diverged significantly from its origins. In today's world, there is a growing awareness and a strong progressive trend. While traditionalists remain and resist thinking beyond what they've been taught, they may not be influential enough to sway the entire population. Among Christians, historical awareness is expected to rise significantly in the coming years, sparking a desire to separate the doctrines added over time from the original intentions of Jesus. This process may take decades or centuries, but it seems inevitable: a significant shift in Christian history will occur, reverting back to its original form. A movement will grow, peeling away layers of doctrine until only the essence of what Jesus introduced remains. When this trend spreads across the United States and Europe, encouraging people to worship as if they were living during Jesus' time, the church as an institution will continue to lead. However, as the theological landscape shifts backward, the diversity within Christianity will give way to increased uniformity in belief and practice. Instead of differences, there will be growing similarities between regions, denominations, and divisions. History is full of such reversions; for example, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, yet that empire later became a Christian institution. Similarly, the country moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The forthcoming reversion will unfold within Christianity, seeking its roots and reducing diversity. An essential part of this process will be interpreting Jesus’ words metaphorically rather than literally. So, what happened since Jesus' time? Looking back in history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the idea of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion by the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish community was not unified, with divisions among Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

I think The Jungle demonstrates that humans are inherently greedy and self-centered, primarily looking out for their own interests and improving their lives, without concern for those below them. The book illustrates this in several ways, notably through the owners and managers of large factories. Their sole focus is on expanding their businesses, without regard for anyone or anything that might suffer due to their progress. Upton Sinclair's description highlights the environmental harm caused by pollution: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair aims to portray the significant damage this smoke causes, showing how the factory owners ignore the impact on people and animals. They disregard the smoke clouds from their factories and the waste runoff from the numerous pens in Packingtown. 

The factory owners and managers were indifferent to the plight of their workers who toiled to enrich them. They would go to any lengths to increase their profits, as illustrated by the notion that "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Employees endured terrible working hours and could be laid off in large numbers without notice, compensation, or assistance in finding new jobs. During the period in which The Jungle is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations to protect workers' safety or welfare. This lack of oversight allowed managers and owners to exploit their workforce, demanding increased productivity under harsh conditions. Although not stated explicitly, the book suggests that those living and working in Packingtown were expected to endure poor conditions both at work and in their living environment. There were no organizations to inform or assist the workers. While unions existed, they often exploited the workers instead of helping them, profiting from their struggles. The workers were treated so poorly, with no escape from the Packingtown system, that they were likened to slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

"Dream-Land" is considered by Edgar Allan Poe to be one of his finer poems. In it, he uses the term "Thulé" twice, in lines 6 and 56, a reference that Mabbott links back to Virgil. Virgil mentioned Thulé as an island north of Britain, which the Greeks believed to be the boundary of the known world. While Virgil indeed used this term, there is also a more contemporary source that deserves attention—Poe's interest in German authors. This connection is significant as it highlights Poe's familiarity with Goethe's works. In his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," Karl J. Arndt discusses the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, suggesting that Poe was influenced by Goethe.

The "Oxford Companion to English Literature" notes that Goethe was renowned for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, with the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of his death. In the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem narrates the story of a king who, after his wife's death, becomes consumed by grief and drinking. He eventually decides to die, passing his possessions to his children, except for a goblet his wife gave him. He throws the goblet into the ocean and dies on a cliff. The somber mood of "The King of Thulé" mirrors the portrayal of the king in "Dream-Land," possibly reflecting Poe's own experiences of loss and reliance on alcohol. Additionally, "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, just before Poe used the term Thulé in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thulé twice in his works: once using "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and twice in "Dream-Land," framing the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes a dark and lonely Thulé, haunted by memories of dead friends and a colorless world. These themes resonate with Goethe's "The King of Thulé," where the king, grieving his wife's death, becomes desolate and loses his will to live. It is as if the speaker in "Dream-Land" is stepping into the world of Goethe’s poem.

Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have been aware of, partly due to his admiration for Tennyson. Poe's exposure to Goethe’s works would have been likely, given their widespread reproductions following their original publication.

In California, could a customer injured by slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be granted punitive damages if the store manager acted with malice, having been informed twice about the spill but neglecting to clean it for 30 minutes due to being on a dinner break? A judge might not immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such a claim, the plaintiff must show that the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm their actions could cause and that the behavior was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have been aware of the potential harm from not cleaning the spill, given that several D&D customers had been injured from similar incidents in the preceding months. Despite this awareness, he still failed to address the spill. While Palmer's claim that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing, it is still reasonable considering that six slip-and-fall accidents occurred in 2009, yet Martin did not take the necessary steps to ensure store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin, on his dinner break, replied that he "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin of the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and suffered a severe back injury. Before Palmer’s accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the claim for punitive damages.

In California, punitive damages can be recovered for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice," according to Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). Malice is defined as conduct intended to cause harm, or if there is no intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and done with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others," as per § (c)(1). Courts have deemed conduct malicious when done with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff’s rights, recognizing the likely dangerous outcomes of the conduct and willfully failing to prevent those outcomes. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt as though something was missing in her life. This insatiable yearning began when she was around 14, just stepping into her teenage years, and persisted even at 17. Over time, she realized she craved someone, not something. However, she hadn't felt drawn to any boys. Some tried to court her, awkwardly attempting to win over someone seemingly uninterested, yet none captured her attention. She frequently pondered this peculiar feeling, trying to understand why it was happening to her. Despite years of reflection leading to various theories, none were convincing enough for her to entertain seriously. So she continued living, always questioning her desires.

A day at home was typically serene. Her parents were calm and kind, rarely arguing with each other and seldom with her. Their only disagreements revolved around her expression of independence and free spirit. Although she was the child of a tranquil couple, her vibrant and lively personality contrasted with theirs, making her very likable due to her kindness.

Today, however, was different. As she wandered from room to room seeking inspiration, she heard a sudden scream from the kitchen, her mother's melodic voice. Panicking, she rushed in, exclaiming, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, clearly in pain, repeatedly gasping "Ow." Her daughter hurried to her side, trying to help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to... the hospital," her mother uttered, her words strained and hurried, conveying her severe discomfort. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up," she responded. Guided by her mother, she managed to carry her, thankful for the strength she had gained from classes. She placed her mother in the back of the car and drove to the hospital.

The hospital visit was filled with the smells of disinfectant and illness, mixed with anxiety. But she wasn't focused on that, her mind was occupied with aiding her mother. She swiftly carried her inside and called for medical assistance. Concerned faces gathered, and someone quickly brought a rolling bed, laying her mother on it. They took her away for immediate medical attention, leaving her daughter to anxiously wait.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while attempting to retrieve a vase from their highest cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a decreased risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related deaths. The aMed diet is an adapted form of the Med diet, characterized by increased intake of plant-based foods like plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (as opposed to saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective research found an inverse relationship between Med diet adherence and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention study revealed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. Previous studies did not specifically address stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without prior CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score on six occasions using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses continued their participation throughout the 20-year duration. FFQs were validated through studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, incidents were classified as "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions categorized this way. For each FFQ, body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated, and from 1986 onward, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed.

To minimize random variation for individuals and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from the previous two years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that might skew results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard models were employed to evaluate the association between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a greater aMed diet score, was linked to a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up period, there were 2,391 new cases of CHD, 1,763 new cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (including fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Ellen Page, known for her role in Juno, is standing by herself on a street corner, holding up a piece of cardboard with this disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also referred to as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a repressive military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, the country saw a series of street protests, the first in a decade. These demonstrations, led by many Burmese monks, were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution" in reference to the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the general public began to support the protests, and while the government initially tolerated the monks' peaceful gatherings, the situation soon escalated into a violent conflict between the monks and the junta. The military began storming and looting monasteries nationwide. Foreign journalists were detained and jailed immediately, and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed on September 27, 2007, just for being at a protest. Although the official death count stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army just before the report was released, claimed, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is not a new phenomenon. While these are some recent examples of global atrocities, the tendency of governments to suppress opposition and maintain total control has existed as long as civilization. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine selection to rule every aspect of society. Japanese emperors were believed to be gods themselves, sent to lead their people to prosperity, with Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri being part of their influence. Meanwhile, our current president, George W. Bush, regularly consults with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subgroup of the Republic Party.

Notable examples of such governmental actions include the June 4, 1989, protest in Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students protested against authoritarian rule. The death toll for this event varies significantly, with Chinese government reports citing 200-300 deaths, while the Chinese Red Cross reported between 2,000-3,000 deaths. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, systematically killed Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's "Third Reich," encompassing several years and countries, involved the mass murder of people of Jewish descent and stands as another extreme instance.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz is largely rooted in his long career and his exceptional talent in shaping his orchestra. While his piano presence is understated in many compositions chosen for this task, Ellington's prowess as a composer shines through his ability to craft intricate and layered pieces that highlight his band members' individual talents. He provided a framework for soloists to improvise freely while also composing tightly orchestrated pieces that leveraged the unique styles of his musicians to bring out musical themes. This approach allowed him to emphasize the overall tone of the orchestra, producing coherent and unique sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's understanding of each player's sound and their role within the ensemble enabled him to create some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, cites "Creole Love Call" as an example of his use of voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This piece showcases Ellington's early use of voice to add texture and color without lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also highlights Ellington's ability to complement his soloists' styles, a trait evident throughout his career. The piece is a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues with six choruses:

Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, starting smooth and melodic, and ending with a rougher tone.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that builds on the basic melody and emphasizes extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, where the reeds initiate the call and response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Returns to the structure of the first chorus, with a call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice uses a "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag with a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending.

Ellington's use of voice to enhance the tonal color in this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait prevalent in his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington merges his skill in tight orchestration with his sensitivity to tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing blends Miley's vocal-like trumpet playing with Cox's instrumental vocal qualities to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" expands on these ideas, with Ellington effectively utilizing Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a key member of his orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the specific ways they do? Are there any limitations or constraints that affect the path of evolutionary change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson remarked that "even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," and this observation still holds true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to broader aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis across both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research aims to investigate how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, along with experimental studies, can clarify the mechanisms behind the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental change. We utilized X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters for modeling both hypothetical and actual skeletal shapes. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We created models of hypothetical shell shapes to interpret the limits of possible morphological change in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to enhance our understanding of macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be considered a structure that acts as a tube traveling over time through 360 degrees of space. The revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are termed whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls grow can vary, and each whorl is separated by a continuous line called a suture. Typically, the largest whorl of a shell is the last one, known as the body whorl. The spire includes all whorls except the last, with the apex being the tip of the spire and the opposite end referred to as the base. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the observer and the apex pointing upwards.)

The following method is used for counting whorls. First, view the shell from the apical perspective and identify where the first suture begins. Then, draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the aperture's path using the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture, as well as the horizontal and vertical radii of the aperture.

This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it becomes possible to adjust parameters and alter the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

Over the past decade, the neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have shown little change. Although the country is progressing towards achieving several Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health are insufficient to meet the 2015 targets. The reasons for these gaps will be explored further, highlighting the need to bolster the health system rather than merely implementing programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has made strides in ensuring that more births are attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now achieving this benchmark. However, this figure includes traditional practitioners like midwives who cannot perform medical interventions in complicated pregnancies, contributing to a high rate of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. Thus, the progress in this area is somewhat deceptive, and significant work remains. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the proportion of children under five receiving professional treatment for diarrhea. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is evident that care rates remain low nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at roughly 4%. This statistic highlights another issue: while urban areas report a 7% c-section rate, rural areas see only 2%, indicating inequitable healthcare coverage across the country. Access is primarily concentrated in urban regions. Additionally, vertical equity is a concern, with a 27% disparity in service utilization between the poorest and richest groups, suggesting that financial barriers hinder the poor from accessing healthcare.

In contemplating the next steps to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how best to tackle service deficiencies. Should Indonesia focus on specific programmatic initiatives or strengthen the overall health system without emphasizing pre and post-pregnancy care? Program-specific approaches are appealing due to their targeted, manageable objectives and generally quicker results. However, these approaches have significant drawbacks. Investing heavily in one health sector area can lead to reduced funding and resources for others, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS affecting the family planning sector. Moreover, running multiple parallel programs leads to redundant and uncoordinated services, resulting in increased paperwork and supply management challenges.

Over the last century, the classification of Popular Music has expanded to such an extent that listing all its genres has become quite challenging. Adding to the complexity, almost all genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have given rise to numerous sub-genres and even sub-sub-genres. Notably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has emerged as one of the most varied and expressive genres in popular music over the past forty years. It is expressive due to its ability to convey a wide array of emotions, though it often leans towards darker themes. It is also diverse, as people quickly realized the genre's flexibility shortly after its inception, leading them to create their own sub-genres and further subdivide those, continuing the trend to the present day.

Currently, the heavy metal scene has diversified into so many niche groups that pinpointing the exact definition of heavy metal is difficult. It has absorbed numerous elements from other genres, yet, like all things, it originated from somewhere. To truly comprehend the metal music that is prevalent today, one must first grasp what the metal movement entails and why it is considered a movement rather than merely a genre.

In many respects, metal is a movement characterized by darkness. It's often described as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more aggression, more theatricality. There's less primitivism and more technical skill, as metal musicians are typically very proficient with their instruments, which is evident in their music. Additionally, metal is, unsurprisingly, a movement heavily influenced by drugs. The psychedelic drug surge in the mid-1970s led to people creating wild, otherworldly records, using drugs as a catalyst for their creativity. It exhibits numerous dark, visceral qualities, a stark contrast to much of the popular music that lacked these darker emotional elements. Later generations of metal have drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral aspects that were prominent during the Romantic Era. Lyrics from songs like "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles illustrate this darkness, representing the emotional highs and lows, possibly influenced by drugs. This song is considered by some as one of the early Heavy Metal tracks and was a response to a darker, heavier Rolling Stones song. The Beatles aimed to prove they could match the heaviness of the Stones, so they included it on "The White Album."

Several decades before Surrealist artists started creating their dreamlike imagery, Henri Rousseau was meticulously crafting his own visions, both literally and metaphorically. His 1910 painting, The Dream, not only depicts a woman marveling at the wonders of a dreamt land but also symbolizes Rousseau's personal ambitions as an artist. From the beginning of his career, he aspired for recognition, acceptance, and admiration from his peers and art enthusiasts, facing a challenging internal conflict to achieve these goals. The Dream best encapsulates Rousseau's lifelong struggle between adhering to or emulating certain artistic styles to gain acceptance in the esteemed art world he admired and maintaining his creative independence and originality.

To understand The Dream from this angle, it's essential to know some of Rousseau's background. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, Henri Rousseau's father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who enjoyed middle-class prosperity (Shattuck 47). Rousseau did not receive formal art training; instead, he worked for France's municipal toll service until the age of forty, earning the mistaken title of douanier, or customs inspector (Shattuck 46). After losing his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their infant children, Rousseau was left with his daughter, Julia, and profound grief (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace, he turned to painting for comfort and a new beginning. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau was fundamentally a folk painter with the aspirations of an average person from his social class.

Rousseau's strong desire for acceptance in the art world is understandable when viewed in context: he lacked formal art education, started his career later in life, and created art alongside many other talented, well-known modern artists. Despite years of work, Rousseau only began receiving proper recognition for his art around the same time Matisse was establishing his artistic reputation. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon notes that although Rousseau and Matisse were technically competitors, they differed not only in style and subject but also in their motivations for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a clichéd way, while Rousseau aimed to create art so conventional that he would be accepted by the Artiste Français" (92).

Many influential thinkers have suggested a deep link between ethics and aesthetics, truth and beauty. I think there's a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” We acquire much of our knowledge through education or experience. Yet, as Keats hints, we seem to understand ethics and aesthetics instinctively, rather than through traditional learning. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than dictate. Our exploration of morality and beauty primarily seeks to explain why a piece of art or a deed is beautiful or moral, instead of providing a checklist for evaluating or creating good art or ethical actions.

Moreover, critiques of art or morals never fully capture the essence of what makes something good or beautiful. Discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on aspects like composition, contrast, or cultural significance, but these don't explain why it's great art. Often, when describing a favorite artwork or literary piece, people say, "There's just something about it" before offering a more detailed critique. I believe that neither art nor morals can be entirely reduced to a list of their features. As Flannery O'Connor notes, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” Even with a thorough description of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I think ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein states, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” I propose that this "something," this indefinable quality, is the most potent aspect of art and morality, and it is this transcendent nature that links ethics and aesthetics.

I believe that morality and art are closely connected because we experience both on a level that is felt rather than fully articulated, aligning with Kantian ideas of the noumenal. This connection is even more pronounced with literature. As McKean observes, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Modern Germany is seen as a powerful and unified nation, with a distinct culture stretching from the Alps' shadows in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This cultural uniqueness is also evident from Cologne along the Rhine River, through central Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. It's no wonder that contemporary Germany is a fusion of various sources and tribes.

The ancient region known as Germania is the ancestral home of the Germans, though the origin of the name is a topic of debate among scholars and historians. Tacitus suggested that the name derived from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, who were referred to as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first mentioned the term “Germanus” in his account of the Gallic Wars, using it to differentiate between the Gauls he had conquered and the Germanic tribes he had not, borrowing the term from the Gauls themselves. Some believe the name referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his initial book on these wars, Caesar noted, “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others argue the name might derive from the spear, known as a ger, used in warfare (O.E.D, 2010), or from the Old Irish word garim, meaning “to shout,” suggesting the Germans were loud or noisy (Names of Germany).

Tacitus, an early Roman historian, wrote in AD 98's “De Origine et situ Germanorum” about the German origins, stating, “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?” (Tacitus, 98)

Why would anyone leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans at that time. They would occasionally send expeditions into Germania for resources and conduct land campaigns, but they mostly returned to their vast empire. As Germanic tribes began emerging in the mid-first century, they lived on the Roman Empire's borders, trading goods from their lands and serving as soldiers in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

The play Twelfth Night suggests that while disguise can be effective for prolonged deception, a person must eventually abandon this false identity to avoid losing themselves entirely. However, ending such deception can lead to feelings of alienation. Ultimately, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. Some may react indifferently to being deceived, but others may take offense at the pretense. Deception involving gender role reversal is especially complex, raising questions about why someone might abandon their identity to adopt that of the opposite gender. In Viola's situation, disguising herself as a man is a means of self-protection: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Newly arrived in an unfamiliar land, Viola finds it necessary to pose as a man to safeguard herself from potential threats. While her plan succeeds, it also isolates her from other women, severing a vital support network. Compounding the issue, Viola is so convincing as a man that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, Viola grapples with unspoken romantic feelings toward Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261). To contemporary readers, Twelfth Night might demonstrate how deception can reveal hidden emotions, particularly for Olivia and Orsino. Some passages suggest that these characters might have unvoiced subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence compels them to confront. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario seems male, or does she secretly have feelings for women? It seems unlikely since Shakespeare's Olivia appears to satirize those who judge others solely on appearance. This is shown by how easily Olivia transfers her affection from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to view Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

Various observers have highlighted the harshness of German colonial rule, particularly concerning the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. However, describing an entire colonial empire with such a simplistic view would be misleading. The German colonial empire's policies and governance were as diverse as its geographical expanse. Similarly, educational opportunities varied across the colonies. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a significant number of educated and literate Africans. German efforts in education in Kamerun and other colonies received acclaim from contemporary writers. 

In contrast, the situation in South West Africa (now Namibia) was markedly different. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and actively participated in the education of the natives, in South West Africa, native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies with minimal government support. However, the government did allocate substantial resources for the education of Europeans, creating state schools and providing greater support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational strategies had long-term impacts on South West Africa, persisting even after the end of German rule. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's differing experience. This paper aims to delve deeper into these factors and highlight new research on settlers' and colonial authorities' attitudes towards native Africans.

There is extensive literature focused specifically on education within the German colonial empire. Most of these works, written in German, date back to the early twentieth century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. The initial aim of these writings was mainly to detail the educational systems in these colonies. Later English-language studies expanded the discussion through comparative analyses of education across different German colonies and more in-depth examinations of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant disparities in the educational systems among the colonies. The most notable work directly addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and explores the factors behind their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounts for many of the unique features of its educational system.

Compared to Germany's other colonies, South West Africa had a relatively moderate climate, despite much of its territory being arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively favorable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans resided in South West Africa, while the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa, had only 5,336.

The United States and Mexico once experienced a prolonged rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this conflict was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two countries, eventually diminishing just before World War I. This rivalry was rooted in clashes over significant issues such as religion, culture, tradition, and material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31). 

Similar to many other nations with enduring rivalries, countries sharing borders often have conflicting interests leading to rivalries. The United States and Mexico exemplify this common pattern among neighboring nations. According to David M.
